<h1>Defaults in Semantics and Pragmatics</h1><div id="pubinfo"><em>First published Fri Jun 30, 2006; substantive revision Tue Jun 30, 2026</em></div>

<div id="preamble">

<p>
&lsquo;Default&rsquo; can mean many different things in theories of
meaning. It is so not only because of the multiplicity of approaches
and dimensions from which meaning can be studied, but also due to the
fact the theoretical landscape, as well as the societal
implementations that are in the focus of public interest, are changing
swiftly. First, there is the dimension of the ongoing debates
concerning the delimitation of explicit (but not necessarly uttered)
content (see Section 1). Second, there has been a growing interest in
speaker accountability for salient but unintended interpretations,
with emphasis on cases of unintentionally causing offence (see Section
5). The latter has to be viewed in the context of the ongoing
&lsquo;revolution&rsquo; in philosophy of language, noticeable in the
progressing departure from analytic philosophy towards applied
philosophy of language, that has brought in debates on socially
expected, or socially and politically correct, and as such, standard,
or <em>default</em>, meanings, spanning discussions on epistemic norms
for assertion (e.g., Goldberg 2015, 2020, 2024; Green 2020; Marsili
2024), theories of argumentation (e.g., Macagno 2022, Oswald 2023),
and, relatedly, as was just mentioned, commitment and accountability
for one&rsquo;s linguistic actions (e.g., Haugh 2013; Geurts 2019;
Borg 2019; Borg &amp; Connolly 2022; Elder 2021; Peet 2022; Mazzarella
2023; Bary 2025, i.a.). For example, defaults are relevant in the
discussions of the conventional import of expressives, in that their
standard expressive (often offensive) meaning may not arise in certain
types of context. The view on what aspects of their meaning are
truth-evaluable is then closely related to the value one attaches to
this context-dependence (Potts 2007, 2012; Richard 2008; Geurts 2007).
&lsquo;Salience&rsquo; and &lsquo;defaultness&rsquo; have also been
discussed contrastively in debates surrounding automatic vs. effortful
retrieval of non-literal interpretations (Giora 2003; Giora &amp;
Givoni 2015; Ariel 2002, 2016). Next, defaultness plays an important
role in computational linguistics, which develops statistical models
for learning compositional meaning using &lsquo;big data&rsquo;
(Jurafsky &amp; Martin 2026 [Other Internet Resources]; Liang &amp;
Potts 2015), and specifically in research on human-AI interaction,
that largely rests on generalizations rather than individual human
intentionality and cognition, be it in the dimension of
addresee-targetted politeness (Ribino 2023), recognising
self-expression (Robbins &amp; Blundell 2026), or temporal dimension
of experience and cognition (Incao <em>et al.</em> 2025), among other
areas of this fast-growing domain of research.</p>

<p>
So, the term &lsquo;default meaning&rsquo; has been used in a variety
of ways in the literature, including statistically common
interpretation, predictable meaning, salient meaning, or automatically
retrieved meaning. To begin with a common-sense definition, default
interpretation of the speaker&rsquo;s utterance is normally understood
to mean salient meaning intended by the speaker, and/or presumed by
the addressee to have been intended, and recovered, (i) without the
help of inference from the speaker&rsquo;s intentions or (ii) without
any conscious inferential process whatsoever. Default interpretations,
interpretations producing the standard content, are defined
differently depending on how &lsquo;default&rsquo; is defined: as a
default for the lexical item, a default for the syntactic structure, a
default for a particular construction, or a default for a particular
context (where, in addition, there is a necessary correlation with the
adopted definition of &lsquo;context&rsquo;). The delimitation of such
defaults can proceed according to different methods, which, again, can
affect the results, and as such further contribute to the definition
of defaults. For example, the psychological route is associated with
automatic, inference-free interpretations, while the statistical route
appeals to quantitative analyses of data, where the latter can pertain
to corpora of conversations or big databases of word co-occurrence as
used in statistical, distributional approaches in computational
semantics. However, with the rise of the research on human-inspired
AI, the picture is now less polarized (see e.g. Cappelen &amp; Dever
2021, 2024).</p>

<p>
In what follows, I attend to some seminal conceptualizations of
defaultness, their provenance, and their relative merits (Sections
1&ndash;3). Section 4 follows with some remarks on what can be called
&lsquo;dynamic defaultness&rsquo; in the theories and models of a
joint construction (&lsquo;co-construction&rsquo;) of meaning that are
steadily gaining ground across different strands of pragmatic research
(Lewis 1979; Asher and Lascarides 2003; Elder and Haugh 2018; Elder
and Jaszczolt 2024). Next, I briefly move to the role of defaults on
the crossroads of philosophy of language with disciplines such as
ethics, epistemology, and law (Section 5). The overview of the major
perspectives and debates makes it clear that there is no consensus in
the literature as to the unique set of properties that default
interpretations should exhibit, opening up the discussion as to
whether the term has only an intra-theoretic utility. Next, of course,
comes the question of the utility of the <em>term</em> and the utility
of the <em>concept</em> &ndash; something I touch upon in the
concluding section in the context of conceptual engineering.</p>
</div> 

